[1
Date: Sun 9 Sep 2001 14:03:06 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Newslink, AP Report, Sun 9 Sep 2001 [edited
<http://www.oweb.com/newslink/international/VenezuelaDengueP0767.html>

Venezuela Update
----------------
CARACAS: A dengue fever epidemic has killed 6 people and [affected more
than 36 600 in Venezuela, the Health Ministry said on Thu 6 Sep 2001. More
than 3000 of the cases involved a potentially fatal form of the
mosquito-borne disease. A total of 36 612 cases have been reported this
year, more than double the figure over the same period last year, the
Ministry said in a statement. It indicated that there were 5838 new cases
last week. A total of 6 people have died this year after contracting dengue
hemorrhagic fever (DHF) following Dengue virus type 3 infection.
There is no vaccine for the disease. Victims suffer headaches, rashes,
cramps, and severe muscle pain. Most recover after a week, but those with
Dengue virus type 3 infection begin to bleed internally even after
appearing to have recovered. Death can result if victims do not receive
medical treatment. On 26 Aug 2001, President Hugo Chavez insisted that the
epidemic was under control and didn't merit a state of emergency, as had
been requested by the Venezuelan Medical Association.
Alfredo Pena, Mayor of greater Caracas, has declared a local emergency in
the capital, where nearly 4800 cases have been reported, including 1061
type-3 cases. Fumigation trucks patrol the streets, and officials are
urging residents to eliminate pools of stagnant water where mosquitos breed.
