[2
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2001 14:42:29 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: La Nacion Costa Rica, Associated Press Report, Fri 7 Sep 2001
[trans. by Mod.MPP and edited

Nicaragua Update
-----------------
MANAGUA: The government has sent medical teams to combat an outbreak of
classical and hemorrhagic dengue fever in the Caribbean region of the north
of the country. At least 5 people have died from dengue hemorrhagic fever
in the Autonomous North Atlantic Region (Caribbean Sea) of the country,
which is located 300 kilometers to the northeast of Managua. The Ministry
of Health stated that the number of dengue fever cases had risen from 44
last year to 85 this year. The last epidemic of dengue occurred in the
country at the end of the 80s.
******
[3
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2001 14:42:29 -0400
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: La Nacion Costa Rica, Fri 7 Sep 2001 [trans. by Mod. MPP and edited
<http://www.nacion.co.cr/ln_ee/2001/septiembre/07/pais7.html>

Costa Rica Update
-----------------
The seasonal rains have been ideal for the _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, the
vector of dengue fever, and [as a consequence there have been 8 persons in
Guanacaste afflicted by dengue hemorrhagic fever. Rogelio Pardo, Minister
of Health, reported that only 3 [of the cases of DHF remain in the Enrique
Baltodano hospital in Liberia, where they are now recuperating. But the
fight is not only concentrated on the cases [of DHF admitted to the
hospital but [also to diminish the cases of classical dengue in the
provinces of Guanacaste, Limon, and Puntarenas.
During July and August, in the Chorotega region of Guanacaste an average of
320 cases of dengue fever were diagnosed per week, but in the last 4 days
this has fallen to 185. Projections are for 5500 cases [of dengue fever
for the year 2001.
In Puntarenas there were 80 cases reported per week during the months of
July and August; now there are 44.
As part of the effort to contain the advance of dengue fever, the Costa
Rican Social Security Institute (CCSS) has invested an additional sum of 72
million Costa Rican colones (approximately US $216 000) in the province of
Guanacaste. The objective is to increase the [number of primary health
care personnel and to educate the residents of the cantons [districts.
When the mosquito vector of dengue fever returned to the country in 1993,
after an absence of 50 years, the number of cases of classical dengue fever
approached 14 000. For this year, the projections of the Ministry of Health
oscillate between 5500 and 6000. In the year 2000, there were 4908 cases of
dengue reported and the highest peak [of reported cases of dengue fever
was in 1997, with 14 421 cases.
