[4
Date: Mon 10 Sep 2001 08:14:11 +0100
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Philippine Daily Inquirer, Wed 5 Sep 2001, and Xinhua News Agency,
Wed 5 Sep 2001 [edited

Philippines Update
-------------------
At least 800 dengue fever cases have been recorded in the province by
August, provincial health officials said. Provincial health office records
showed that the number of people afflicted with dengue fever this year has
tripled compared to last year's figures. The fifth dengue fatality recorded
in Pangasinan this year was a 5-month-old baby girl from Bolinao town.
Governor Victor Agbayani ordered the 14 public hospitals in the province to
treat dengue patients without charge and provide them with medicines.
Health Secretary Manuel Dayrit warned on Wednesday that cases of dengue
fever could continue to rise and cause another epidemic if prevention and
control measures are not sustained. The warning came as health experts
disclosed that the number of dengue cases is expected to peak this month or
in October. "Dengue cases will continue to rise but prompt referral and
proper case management will decrease the number of deaths," Dayrit told
reporters. Dayrit urged local government officials to assist her department
in identifying hot spots and high-risk areas, creating dengue watch at the
village level and in intensifying information dissemination on mosquito
control.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
