Date: Fri 7 Sep 2001
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Xinhua News Agency, Fri 7 Sep 2001 and Business Recorder, September
5th, 2001 [edited

Bangladesh Update
-----------------
BANGLADESH: At least 8 people have died of dengue fever in the country and
about 573 have been afflicted by the disease as of 7 Sep 2001, according to
official sources here on Friday. Unofficial sources, however, believe that
the actual number of dengue cases so far is much higher. In the capital,
many dengue patients are rushing to different hospitals and clinics
everyday. Experts believe that this year's dengue outbreak may be less
serious than that of the last year. Unlike the situation in the previous
year, the physicians as well as the people are now aware of the disease.
More is known about its identification and case management. Last year, 93
persons reportedly died of dengue and a total of 5551 persons were attacked
by the disease.
Some 15 000 people have been infected with dengue fever in the Bangladeshi
capital Dhaka and its surroundings, one year after the disease killed 70 in
the country, hospital and media reports said on Tuesday. Only 2 people are
known to have died from the disease this year in Dhaka, but about 4 times
as many people have contracted dengue fever compared with last year.
Doctors said the disease has spread because of an ongoing dry spell
following last week's heavy monsoon rains, conditions that help the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquitoes which carry the virus to breed quickly.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
