[6
Date: Fri 7 Sep 2001
From: Pablo Nart <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: AP Worldstream, Thu 6 Sep 2001 [edited

Singapore Update
----------------
SINGAPORE: Cases of the sometimes fatal mosquito-borne disease dengue fever
have surged in Singapore, a news report said Thursday. A total of 953 new
dengue cases were reported from July through August, up sharply from the
892 cases in the first 6 months of this year, The Straits Times newspaper
reported. Singapore has a population of about 4 million.
Officials at Singapore's Environment Ministry, which tracks dengue cases,
would not immediately comment on the report. A 28-year-old woman died from
dengue in Singapore in August, the only death from the disease reported
this year, the newspaper said. Dengue has remained a problem in Singapore
despite spraying, public education campaigns and increased fines for those
found with mosquitoes breeding on their property. Controlling the insects
is difficult in Singapore, a tropical island which is regularly drenched by
monsoon rains.
--
Pablo Nart
